, 'Like a gardener  I believe that what goes down must come up.', 63029, 0), (411038, 'Nature is a catchment of sorrows.', 64827, 0), (411039, 'Nature is not human-hearted.', 15, 0), (411040, 'Nature  with equal mind  sees all her sons at play  sees man control the wind  the wind sweep man away.', 460, 0), (411041, 'The chess-board is the world  the pieces are the phenomena of the universe  the rules of the game are what we call the Laws of Nature. The player on the other side is hidden from us. We know that his play is always fair  just and patient. But also we know  to our cost  that he never overlooks a mistake  or makes the smallest allowance for ignorance.', 63366, 0), (411042, 'The sky is the daily bread of the eyes.', 760, 0), (411043, 'The unnatural - that too is natural.', 62192, 0), (411044, 'There is one glory of the sun and another glory of the moon and another glory of the stars: for one star differeth from another star in glory.', 5587, 0), (411045, 'There is something haunting in the light of the moon  it has all the dispassionateness of a disembodied soul  and something of its inconceivable mystery.', 1241, 0), (411046, 'The universe is not hostile  nor yet is it friendly. It is simply indifferent.', 64828, 0), (411047, 'In nature there are neither rewards nor punishments - there are consequences.', 1980, 0), (411048, 'Monotony is the law of nature. Look at the monotonous manner in which the sun rises. The monotony of necessary occupations is exhilarating and life-giving.', 32, 0), (411049, 'Men argue  nature acts.', 808, 0), (411050, 'Nature is usually wrong.', 59297, 0);
INSERT INTO quotes (id, content, author_id, views) VALUES (411051, 'Speak to the earth  and it shall teach thee.', 5587, 0), (411052, 'Flowers have an expression of countenance as much as men or animals. Some seem to smile  some have a sad expression  some are pensive and diffident  others again are plain  honest and upright.', 2175, 0), (411053, 'Gie me a spark o'' nature''s fire  that''s a'' the learning I desire.', 1606, 0), (411054, 'Light may be shed on man and his origins.', 1024, 0), (411055, 'I have called this principle  by which each slight variation  if useful  is preserved  by the term natural selection.', 1024, 0), (411056, 'The expression often used by Mr. Herbert Spencer  of the "Survival of the fittest"  is more accurate  and is sometimes equally convenient.', 1024, 0), (411057, 'Nature is reckless of the individual. When she has points to carry  she carries them', 760, 0), (411058, 'I wanted to say something about the universe. There''s God  angels  plants... and horseshit.', 64829, 0), (411059, 'When elephants fight it is the grass that suffers.', 64830, 0), (411060, 'The dinosaur''s eloquent lesson is that if some bigness is good  an overabundance of bigness is not necessarily better.', 64831, 0), (411061, 'Who are we? We find that we live on an insignificant planet of a humdrum star lost in a galaxy tucked away in some forgotten corner of a universe in which there are far more galaxies than people.', 133, 0), (411062, 'A vacuum is a hell of a lot better than some of the stuff that nature replaces it with.', 355, 0), (411063, 'We cannot command Nature except by obeying her.', 1035, 0), (411064, 'The mastery of nature is vainly believed to be an adequate substitute for self-mastery.', 1779, 0), (411065, 'Nature thrives on patience  man on impatience.', 64832, 0), (411066, 'The soil  in return for her service  keeps the tree tied to her  the sky asks nothing and leaves it free.', 430, 0), (411067, 'What mighty battles have I seen and heard waged between the trees and the west wind - an Iliad fought in the fields of air.', 63323, 0), (411068, 'Grass is the forgiveness of nature - her constant benediction. Forests decay  harvests perish  flowers vanish  but grass is immortal.', 64833, 0), (411069, 'I frequently tramped eight or ten miles through the deepest snow to keep an appointment with a beech tree  or a yellow birch  or an old acquaintance among the pines.', 1049, 0), (411070, 'The whole of nature is a conjugation of the verb to eat  in the active and passive.', 62527, 0), (411071, 'The universe is like a safe to which there is a combination  but the combination is locked up in the safe.', 2274, 0), (411072, 'When the oak is felled the whole forest echoes with its fall  but a hundred acorns are sown in silence by an unnoticed breeze.', 3061, 0), (411073, 'Deep in their roots  all flowers keep the light.', 1085, 0), (411074, 'By nature''s kindly disposition  most questions which it is beyond man''s power to answer do not occur to him at all.', 2683, 0), (411075, 'To demand ''sense'' is the hallmark of nonsense. Nature does not make sense. Nothing makes sense.', 631, 0), (411076, 'The bluebird carries the sky on his back.', 1049, 0), (411077, 'There is nothing in which the birds differ more from man than the way in which they can build and yet leave a landscape as it was before.', 44024, 0), (411078, 'The greatest joy in nature is the absence of man.', 8765, 0), (411079, 'When a man wantonly destroys a work of man we call him a vandal  when a man destroys one of the works of God  we call him a sportsman.', 38001, 0), (411080, 'Man is a complex being: he makes deserts bloom and lakes die.', 64834, 0), (411081, 'Nature never did betray the heart that loved her.', 2063, 0), (411082, 'God''s miracles are to be found in nature itself  the wind and waves  the wood that becomes a tree - all of these are explained biologically  but behind them is the hand of God.', 1727, 0), (411083, 'When I first open my eyes upon the morning meadows and look out upon the beautiful world  I thank God I am alive.', 760, 0), (411084, 'If you wish to know the divine  feel the wind on your face and the warm sun on your hand.', 64835, 0), (411085, 'The radiance in some places is so great as to be fairly dazzling . . . every crystal  every flower a window opening into heaven  a mirror reflecting the Creator.', 1402, 0), (411086, 'Nature is too thin a screen  the glory of the omnipresent God bursts through everywhere.', 760, 0), (411087, 'I believe a leaf of grass is no less than the journey-work of the stars.', 1127, 0), (411088, 'Look deep  deep into nature  and then you will understand everything better.', 104, 0), (411089, 'Come forth into the light of things. Let nature be your teacher.', 2063, 0), (411090, 'If you watch how nature deals with adversity  continually renewing itself  you can''t help but learn.', 64551, 0), (411091, 'Rivers and rocks and trees have always been talking to us  but we''ve forgotten how to listen.', 64836, 0), (411092, 'Speak to the earth  and it shall teach thee.', 5587, 0), (411093, 'Adopt the pace of nature: her secret is patience.', 760, 0), (411094, 'Climb the mountains and get their good tidings: Nature''s peace will flow into you as sunshine into flowers  the winds will blow their freshness into you  and the storms  their energy and cares will drop off like autumn leaves.', 1402, 0), (411095, 'Nature tops the list of potent tranquilizers and stress reducers. The mere sound of moving water has been shown to lower blood pressure.', 5890, 0), (411096, 'The sun - my almighty physician.', 1207, 0), (411097, 'Nature uses only the longest threads to weave her patterns  so each small piece of her fabric reveals the organization of the entire tapestry.', 582, 0), (411098, 'The finest workers in stone are not copper or steel tools  but the gentle touches of air and water working at their leisure with a liberal allowance of time.', 1049, 0), (411099, 'To the dull mind all nature is leaden. To the illumined mind the whole world burns and sparkles with light.', 760, 0), (411100, 'The beauty of the world and the orderly arrangement of everything celestial makes us confess that there is an excellent and eternal nature  which ought to be worshiped and admired by all mankind.', 20928, 0);
INSERT INTO quotes (id, content, author_id, views) VALUES (411101, 'In all things of nature there is something of the marvelous.', 1116, 0), (411102, 'The sun gives us light  but the moon provides inspiration. If you look at the sun without shielding your eyes  you''ll go blind. If you look at the moon without covering your eyes  you''ll become a poet.', 64837, 0), (411103, 'The world is full of poetry. The air is living with its spirit  and the waves dance to the music of its melodies  and sparkle in its brightness.', 64838, 0), (411104, 'The sky is the daily bread of the eyes.', 64839, 0), (411105, 'My heart leaps up when I behold a rainbow in the sky.', 2063, 0), (411106, 'The bluebird carries the sky on his back.', 1049, 0), (411107, 'The clearest way into the Universe is through a forest wilderness.', 1402, 0), (411108, 'We lose our souls if we lose the experience of the forest  the butterflies  the song of the birds  if we can''t see the stars at night.', 64840, 0), (411109, 'Forget not that the earth delights to feel your bare feet and the winds long to play with your hair.', 81, 0), (411110, 'As long as the Earth can make a spring every year  I can. As long as the Earth can flower and produce nurturing fruit  I can  because I''m the Earth. I won''t give up until the Earth gives up.', 753, 0), (411111, 'The creation of a thousand forests is in one acorn.', 760, 0), (411112, 'I never knew how soothing trees are - many trees and patches of open sunlight  and tree presences  it is almost like having another being.', 178, 0), (411113, 'Nature is saturated with deity.', 760, 0), (411114, 'Our Lord has written the promise of resurrection  not in books alone but in every leaf of springtime.', 1746, 0), (411115, 'The nicest thing about the promise of spring is that sooner or later she''ll have to keep it.', 64841, 0), (411116, 'Spring is nature''s way of saying  "Let''s party!"', 2185, 0), (411117, 'It was one of those perfect summer days - the sun was shining  a breeze was blowing  the birds were singing  and the lawnmower was broken.', 60491, 0), (411118, 'Nobody sees a flower - really - it is so small it takes time -  we haven''t time - and to see takes time  like to have a friend takes time.', 1944, 0), (411119, 'Consider the lilies of the field  how they grow  they neither toil nor spin  yet I tell you  even Solomon in all his glory was not arrayed like one of these.', 5587, 0), (411120, 'The AmenT of Nature is always a flower.', 24754, 0), (411121, 'Next time a sunrise steals your breath or a meadow of flowers leave you speechless  remain that way. Say nothing  and listen as heaven whispers  "Do you like it? I did it just for you."', 86, 0), (411122, 'Every flower is a soul blossoming in Nature.', 16473, 0), (411123, 'Flowers always make people better  happier  and more helpful  they are sunshine  food  and medicine to the soul.', 3603, 0), (411124, 'Earth laughs in flowers.', 760, 0), (411125, 'God Almighty first planted a garden. And indeed it is the purest of human pleasures.', 1035, 0), (411126, 'Pleasure for an hour  a bottle of wine  pleasure for a year  marriage  pleasure for a lifetime  a garden.', 62569, 0), (411127, 'The kiss of sun for pardon  The song of the birds for mirth One is nearer God''s Heart in a garden Than anywhere else on earth.', 64842, 0), (411128, 'All gardeners live in beautiful places because they make them so.', 8895, 0), (411129, 'All gardening is landscape painting.', 3348, 0), (411130, 'What is a weed? A plant whose virtues have not yet been discovered.', 760, 0), (411131, 'For many years I was self-appointed inspector of snowstorms and rainstorms  and did my duty faithfully  though I never received one cent for it.', 1049, 0), (411132, 'The next time it begins to rain ... lie down on your belly  nestle your chin into the grass  and get a frog''s-eye view of how raindrops fall . . . The sight of hundreds of blades of grass bowing down and popping back up like piano keys strikes me as one of the merriest sights in the world.', 52236, 0), (411133, 'Sunshine is delicious  rain is refreshing  wind braces us up  snow is exhilarating  there is really no such thing as bad weather  only different kinds of good weather.', 485, 0), (411134, 'Don''t knock the weather  nine-tenths of the people couldn''t start a conversation if it didn''t change once in a while.', 14120, 0), (411135, 'After rain comes fair weather.', 44934, 0), (411136, 'Weather means more when you have a garden. There''s nothing like listening to a shower and thinking how it is soaking in around your green beans.', 63122, 0), (411137, 'This is the day the Lord had made. We will rejoice and be glad in it.', 5587, 0), (411138, 'I have always been delighted at the prospect of a new day  a fresh try  one more start  with perhaps a bit of magic waiting somewhere behind the morning.', 47328, 0), (411139, 'Whether one is twenty  forty  or sixty  whether one has succeeded  failed or just muddled along  whether yesterday was full of sun or storm  or one of those dull days with no weather at all  life begins each morning I', 63561, 0), (411140, 'Today a new sun rises for me  everything lives  everything is animated  everything seems to speak to me of my passion  everything invites me to cherish it.', 64773, 0), (411141, 'Every new day begins with possibilities. It''s up to us to fill it with the things that move us toward progress and peace.', 1727, 0), (411142, 'I love the challenge of starting at zero every day and seeing how much I can accomplish.', 37848, 0), (411143, 'Thank God ever morning when you get up that you have something to do which must be done  whether you like it or not.', 3036, 0), (411144, 'Today is a new day. You will get out of it just what you put into it. . . If you have made mistakes  even serious mistakes  there is always another chance for you. . . . for this thing that we call "failure" is not the falling down  but the staying down.', 3277, 0), (411145, 'Finish each day and be done with it. You have done what you could  some blunders and absurdities have crept in  forget them as soon as you can. Tomorrow is a new day  you shall begin it serenely and with too high a spirit to be encumbered with your old nonsense.', 760, 0), (411146, 'Live your life each day as you would climb a mountain. An occasional glance toward the summit keeps the goal in mind  but many beautiful scenes are to be observed from each new vantage point. Climb slowly  steadily  enjoying each passing moment  and the view from the summit will serve as a fitting climax for the journey.', 37876, 0), (411147, 'Nothing is worth more than this day.', 62192, 0), (411148, 'Write it on your heart that every day is the best day in the year.', 760, 0), (411149, 'Normal day  let me be aware of the treasure you are. Let me learn from you  love you  bless you before you depart. Let me not pass you by in quest of some rare and perfect tomorrow.', 62693, 0), (411150, 'Yesterday is not ours to recover  but tomorrow is ours to win or lose.', 1763, 0);
INSERT INTO quotes (id, content, author_id, views) VALUES (411151, 'When all else is lost  the future still remains.', 7233, 0), (411152, 'When I look at the future  it''s so bright  it burns my eyes.', 588, 0), (411153, 'Earth''s crammed with Heaven  And every common bush afire with God.', 62884, 0), (411154, 'To him who in the love of Nature holds Communion with her visible forms  she speaks A various language.', 8277, 0), (411155, 'I love not man the less  but nature more.', 62558, 0), (411156, 'For Art may err  but Nature cannot miss.', 8695, 0), (411157, 'The woods were made for the hunter of dreams  The brooks for the fishes of song.', 64387, 0), (411158, 'Nature is a volume of which God is the author.', 2063, 0), (411159, 'Nature  like a kind and smiling mother  lends herself to our dreams and cherishes our fancies.', 98, 0), (411160, 'Accuse not Nature  she hath done her part  Do thou but thine!', 465, 0), (411161, 'Grass is the forgiveness of nature - her constant benediction. ... Forests decay  harvests perish  flowers vanish  but grass is immortal.', 64843, 0), (411162, 'Everything in nature acts in conformity with law.', 1275, 0), (411163, 'Nature abhors a vacuum.', 1013, 0), (411164, 'To hold  as ''t were  the mirror up to nature.', 13, 0), (411165, 'I chatter  chatter  as I flow To join the brimming river  For men may come and men may go  But I go on forever.', 62337, 0), (411166, 'When I would recreate myself  I seek the darkest wood  the thickest and most interminable  and to the citizen  most dismal swamp. I enter a swamp as a sacred place -  a sanctum sanctorum. There is the strength  the marrow of Nature.', 1049, 0), (411167, 'One touch of nature makes the whole world kin.', 13, 0), (411168, 'Nature has always had more force than education.', 808, 0), (411169, 'O pilot! ''tis a fearful night  There''s danger on the deep.', 62199, 0), (411170, 'The winds and waves are always on the side of the ablest navigators.', 7427, 0), (411171, 'Oh  I am a cook and a captain bold And the mate of the Nancy brig  And a bo''sun tight and a midshipmate And the crew of the captain''s gig.', 6987, 0), (411172, 'Thus  I steer my bark  and sail On even keel  with gentle gale.', 29601, 0), (411173, 'Hearts of oak are our ships  Hearts of oak are our men.', 64483, 0), (411174, 'Now landsmen all  whoever you may be  If you want to rise to the top of the tree. If your soul isn''t fettered to an office stool  Be careful to be guided by this golden rule -  Stick close to your desks and never go to to sea  And you may all be Rulers of the Queen''s Navee.', 6987, 0), (411175, 'Necessity has no law.', 33, 0), (411176, 'Necessity  the mother of invention.', 33, 0), (411177, 'Necessity is often the spur to genius.', 143, 0), (411178, 'Necessity is the plea for every infringement of human freedom. It is the argument of tyrants  it is the creed of slaves.', 64506, 0), (411179, 'Necessity makes even the timid brave.', 4812, 0), (411180, 'Not for myself I make this prayer  But for this race of mine That stretches forth from shadowed places Dark hands for bread and wine.', 46929, 0), (411181, 'The image of God cut in ebony.', 1348, 0), (411182, 'O black and unknown bards of long ago  How came your lips to touch the sacred fire? How  in your darkness  did you come to know The power and beauty of the minstrel''s lyre?', 12431, 0), (411183, 'In the Negro countenance you will often meet with strong traits of benignity. I have felt yearnings of tenderness towards some of these faces.', 2182, 0), (411184, 'The best way to uncolor the Negro is to give the white man a white heart.', 62423, 0), (411185, 'The Negro is an exotic of the most gorgeous and superb countries of the world  and he has deep in his heart a passion for all that is splendid  rich and fanciful.', 3252, 0), (411186, 'We can live without our friends but not without our neighbors.', 1348, 0), (411187, 'When your neighbor''s house is afire your own property is at stake.', 2542, 0), (411188, 'Thou shalt love thy neighbor as thyself.', 64491, 0), (411189, 'The crop always seems better in our neighbor''s field  and our neighbor''s cow gives more milk.', 782, 0), (411190, 'In the field of world policy I would dedicate this nation to the policy of the good neighbor.', 62485, 0), (411191, 'The cold neutrality of an impartial judge.', 2026, 0), (411192, 'Neutrality  as a lasting principle  is an evidence of weakness.', 63735, 0), (411193, 'A wise neuter joins with neither  but uses both  as his honest interest leads him.', 3256, 0), (411194, 'The heart is never neutral.', 64844, 0), (411195, 'A plague o'' both your houses.', 13, 0), (411196, 'A man never tells you anything until you contradict him.', 266, 0), (411197, 'Laws die  books never.', 5223, 0), (411198, 'We are never deceived  we deceive ourselves.', 62192, 0), (411199, 'The English never draw a line without blurring it.', 3621, 0), (411200, 'Deep experience is never peaceful.', 561, 0);
